**Abstract:**
Brief working notes titled "Finding my way. Essay One." The document outlines two fundamental directions in medieval thought: the primacy of intellect-truth-evidence-vision-contemplation vs. the primacy of love-will-practical adherence. It identifies Aquinas with the former and Kilwardby as leader of "Augustinisme philosophique" opposing Aristotelico-Thomism. Notes that Kant's division of pure and practical reason led to faith being treated as blind postulates, reflecting Kant's implicit evidentialism.

**AI Recommendation:** Preliminary orientation notes; sketches the evidentialism-voluntarism opposition central to the Chantilly project.

